root.tree-val: Proto Thura-Yura, subtree of Pama-Nyungan: Hercus and Simpson 2004
root.pub-comments: "We call this group 'Thura-Yura' (TY) in recognition of the th > y lenition which distinguishes the northern members of the subgroup. We reconstruct at two levels, the core TY languages (pcTY), and the greater group consisting of the core languages and Wirangu (pTY)" ( Hercus and Simpson 2004: 197). The language Nauo was not definitively placed anywhere in this subgrouping, but the authors acknowledge that "the few Nauo words recorded suggest a language intermediate between Wirangu and Barngarla (Hercus and Simpson 2001); so it too may be part of this Sprachbund" (Hercus and Simpson 2004: 182).
root.publications: Hercus, Luise Anna & Jane H. Simpson. 2004. Thura Yura as a subgroup. In Claire Bowern & Harold Koch (eds.), Australian Languages: The classification and comparative method, vol. 249, 179-206. Amsterdam: John Benjamins.

child.tree-val: Proto Thura-Yura, subtree of Pama-Nyungan: Hercus and Simpson 2004
child.pub-comments: "We examine the grammatical forms shared between the northern and southern Thura-Yura languages and propose reconstructions for 'proto core Thura-Yura' (pcTY), that is all the Thura-Yura languages except Wirangu and Nauo if reflexes are found in both the southern and northern groups: we use caution with data from Ngadjuri and Nukunu for reconstructions at the pcTY level because there is not enough evidence to group them definitively either with the southern or with the northern TY languages. If reconstructed pcTY forms are shared with Wirangu, then we attempt reconstruction at the proto Thura-Yura level (pTY)" (Hercus and Simpson 2004: 183).
child.publications: Hercus, Luise Anna & Jane H. Simpson. 2004. Thura Yura as a subgroup. In Claire Bowern & Harold Koch (eds.), Australian Languages: The classification and comparative method, vol. 249, 179-206. Amsterdam: John Benjamins.

child.tree-val: Proto Thura-Yura, subtree of Pama-Nyungan: Hercus and Simpson 2004
child.pub-comments: "We argue for the inclusion of Wirangu as an outlier of the subgroup. By the term 'outlier' we imply that this language shows some differences from the rest of the subgroup: we suggest that these differences are not genetic, but due to profound changes that have taken place in relatively recent times owing to the influence of Western Desert languages" (Hercus and Simpson 2004: 179).
child.publications: Hercus, Luise Anna & Jane H. Simpson. 2004. Thura Yura as a subgroup. In Claire Bowern & Harold Koch (eds.), Australian Languages: The classification and comparative method, vol. 249, 179-206. Amsterdam: John Benjamins.
